{"id":"1110.1392","submitter":"Giovanni Sordi","authors":"G. Sordi, P. S\\'emon, K. Haule and A.-M. S. Tremblay","title":"Pseudogap temperature as a Widom line in doped Mott insulators","comments":"6 pages, 4 figures and supplementary information; published version","journal-ref":"Scientific Reports 2, 547 (2012)","doi":"10.1038/srep00547","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el cond-mat.stat-mech cond-mat.supr-con","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The pseudogap refers to an enigmatic state of matter with unusual physical\nproperties found below a characteristic temperature $T^*$ in hole-doped\nhigh-temperature superconductors. Determining $T^*$ is critical for\nunderstanding this state. Here we study the simplest model of correlated\nelectron systems, the Hubbard model, with cluster dynamical mean-field theory\nto find out whether the pseudogap can occur solely because of strong coupling\nphysics and short nonlocal correlations. We find that the pseudogap\ncharacteristic temperature $T^*$ is a sharp crossover between different\ndynamical regimes along a line of thermodynamic anomalies that appears above a\nfirst-order phase transition, the Widom line. The Widom line emanating from the\ncritical endpoint of a first-order transition is thus the organizing principle\nfor the pseudogap phase diagram of the cuprates. No additional broken symmetry\nis necessary to explain the phenomenon. Broken symmetry states appear in the\npseudogap and not the other way around.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 6 Oct 2011 20:50:47 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 1 Aug 2012 09:40:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-08-02"}
